Fukushima and the collapse of derivative products
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have equated the earthquakes, tsunami and nuclear disaster in Japan to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The similarity is quite clear: each of these activities generates huge profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
Yet, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with usually harmless design flaws, caused the interruption of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
In terms of financial markets, an unexpected collapse of real estate values, combined with design flaws in derivative products and repos, damaged the ability of major financial institutions to honor their debts.
Although the basic risks originate outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, overinvestment in mortgage loans for financial institutions – design flaws and a lack of luck made it so that the systems could not contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivative products and/or repos – went bankrupt, causing a freeze in credit on the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand quite well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
We cannot say the same about the risks of derivative products that shook the global economy.
A Fukushima, les équipes de travailleurs tentent vaillamment de stopper les fuites de radiation.
Par contre, pour les produits dérivés, les efforts analogues sont mal dirigés et ne nous permettront pas d’éviter la prochaine crise financière.
Nous sommes en train de recréer des produits dérivés et des structures financières similaires, par-dessus les mêmes erreurs qui sont toujours actives.
Les acteurs financiers utilisent les produits financiers pour transférer le risque : par exemple, un acteur accepte le risque de la fluctuation de l’euro mais ne veut pas du risque sur le yen, alors que pour un autre, ce sera le contraire.
Dans ce cas, le premier promet de fournir des euros au 1er juin, et le deuxième promet de fournir des yens.
If a currency loses value compared to the other, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bills or mortgage debts, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the next day (hence the name "repo," which is an abbreviation for the English verb "repurchase" – or to buy back, note).
The problem is that the cash from these short-term repos represents a large part of the balance sheets of the most important financial institutions, which implies that even small financial tremors can affect them significantly.
Some institutions can then find themselves without repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, as Bear Stearns did.
Individually, transactions on derivatives or repos are hardly blameworthy.
Each separately legitimately transfers risk to those better able to bear it, or allows for financial participation.
However, when used excessively by institutions that are vital at the systemic level, they can explode the financial system, due to its design flaws.
Even today, nearly 70% of the liabilities of major US financial firms are composed of very short-term loans, such as repos payable the next day.
In the United States, the main design flaws are found in bankruptcy law, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in the case of bankruptcy.
For example, investors who hold derivative contracts or repos with weakened financial institutions can seize the company's assets before – and at the expense of – its normal creditors. In doing so, they can decide the company's fate, whereas, with a little more time, the company in question could have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos find themselves at the front of the repayment line in so many ways, they have less incentive to encourage market discipline by closely examining the solvency of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be repaid, anyway.
Of course, someone must be first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because the exemptions for actors in derivatives and repo place these actors first in line in the event of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect that the others would therefore have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the actor that follows in line is often the U.S. government, as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions. However, the government is poorly positioned to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile; it often confines itself to the regulated market; and, when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The U.S. Congress had an opportunity to address this flaw in the major overhaul of finance that it adopted last summer through the Dodd Frank bill.
But he did not seize it.
If investors in derivatives, repos, and credit-default swaps (credit event derivatives, note) did not enjoy favorable treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would insist more often that their counterparties are adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk generated by extremely low capitalizations when it was essentially U.S. government money; they would be less inclined to do so if it was their own money they were risking.
The public perceives risks of the Fukushima type and risks related to derivatives differently.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are striking, causing a slowdown in the sector that must deal with security concerns.
But the derivatives and repos markets present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to discuss and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract the attention and disdain of the public, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Regarding risks of the Fukushima type, analysts are already discussing how nuclear plants can be designed and built to contain risks related to earthquakes and tsunamis through passive cooling systems.
Today, it is considered possible to design nuclear plants capable of maintaining cold fuel rods even in the case of a complete power outage.
However, few significant progress has been made so far in order to prevent the damages that the priority of derivatives and repos in case of bankruptcy could generate during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require that end-users (such as oil companies using derivatives to protect against unexpected price changes in oil) and others post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main issue: the low incentives for market discipline for the major financial institutions.
It is as if we were reacting to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully place the risk related to their decisions on investors in derivatives and repos when they carry out transactions with financial institutions that are vital at the systemic level.
Instead, we have survived the 2008 financial tsunami only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same defective design.
